    </introduction>

    <subsection>
    	<title>Definition of Polynomial</title>

	    <definition xml:id="definition-polynomial">
	        <title>Polynomial</title>
	        <index><main>polynomial</main></index>
            <statement>
                <p>In mathematics, a <term>polynomial</term> is an expression consisting of <term>variables</term><index><main>variable</main></index> and <term>coefficients</term><index><main>coefficient</main></index>, that involves only the operations of addition, subtraction, multiplication, and non-negative integer exponents. An example of a polynomial of a single variable <m>x</m> is <m>x^2−4x+7</m>. An example in three variables is <m>x^3+2xyz^2−yz+1</m>. (Visit <url href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Polynomial">Wikipedia</url> for more.)</p>
            </statement>
        </definition>

    	<p>A polynomial consists of <term>terms</term><index><main>term</main></index>. For example, the polynomial <m>x^2-4x+7</m> has 3 terms: <m>x^2</m>, <m>-4x</m> and <m>7</m>.</p>

    	<p>A polynomial may not have terms with negative or non-integer exponents. This implies a polynomial may not have variables in a fraction's denominator, and a polynomial also may not have variables inside a square root (or other types of root). The following expressions do not qualify as polynomials:<ul>
    		<li><p><m>x^{-2}-4x+7</m></p></li>
    		<li><p><m>\frac{1}{x^2}-4x+7</m></p></li>
    		<li><p><m>x^{\frac{1}{2}}-4x+7</m></p></li>
    		<li><p><m>\sqrt{x}+7</m></p></li>
    	</ul>However, numbers in a polynomial may have negative or non-integer exponents. The following expressions do qualify as polynomials:<ul>
    		<li><p><m>x^2-4^{-2}x+7</m></p></li>
    		<li><p><m>\frac{1}{2}x^2-4x+7</m></p></li>
    		<li><p><m>x^2-4x+7^{\frac{1}{2}}</m></p></li>
    		<li><p><m>x\sqrt{2}+7</m></p></li>
    	</ul></p>

    	<p>The term with the highest exponent is called the polynomial's <term>leading term</term><index><main>leading term</main></index>, and that exponent is called the polynomial's <term>degree</term><index><main>degree</main></index>. For example, the degree of the polynomial <m>x^2-4x+7</m> is <m>2</m>. Or, we say <m>x^2-4x+7</m> is a second-degree polynomial. There are some special names for polynomials with some common degrees:<ul>
    		<li><p>A zero-degree polynomial is called a <term>constant polynomial</term> (because <m>7=7x^0</m>).</p></li>
    		<li><p>A first-degree polynomial is called a <term>linear polynomial</term> (such as <m>2x+3</m>).</p></li>
    		<li><p>A second-degree polynomial is called a <term>quadratic polynomial</term> (such as <m>x^2-4x+7</m>).</p></li>
    		<li><p>A third-degree polynomial is called a <term>cubic polynomial</term> (such as <m>x^3-4x+7</m>).</p></li>
    		<li><p>A fourth-degree polynomial is called a <term>quartic polynomial</term> (rarely used).</p></li>
    		<li><p>A fifth-degree polynomial is called a <term>quintic polynomial</term> (rarely used).</p></li>
    	</ul>To help us recognize a polynomial's degree, we should always order a polynomial's terms by their exponents. For example, we should do<me>7-4x+x^2=x^2-4x+7</me></p>

    	<p>For a polynomial with multiple variables, we need to add up all variables' exponent to find a term's degree. For example, polynomial <m>2x^2y+2x^2+3x-10y</m> has a degree of <m>3</m>. In its leading term <m>2x^2y</m>, <m>x^2</m>'s exponent is <m>2</m> and <m>y</m>'s exponent is <m>1</m>, so its leading term's degree is <m>2+1=3</m>.</p>

    	<p>The coefficient of a polynomial's leading term is called the polynomial's <term>leading coefficient</term><index><main>leading coefficient</main></index>. For example, the leading coefficient of <m>x^2-4x+7</m> is <m>1</m> (because <m>x^2=1\cdot x^2</m>).</p>

    	<p>The term with no variables is called the polynomial's <term>constant term</term><index><main>constant term</main></index>. For example, the constant term of <m>x^2-4x+7</m> is <m>7</m>.</p>

    	<p>There are special names for polynomials with a small number of terms:<ul>
    		<li><p>A polynomial with one term is called a <term>monomial</term><index><main>monomial</main></index>, such as <m>3x^5</m> and <m>9</m>.</p></li>
    		<li><p>A polynomial with two terms is called a <term>binomial</term><index><main>binomial</main></index>, such as <m>3x^5+2x</m> and <m>-2x+1</m>.</p></li>
    		<li><p>A polynomial with three terms is called a <term>trinomial</term><index><main>trinomial</main></index>, such as <m>x^2-4x+7</m>.</p></li>
    	</ul>There are no special names for polynomials with more than 3 terms.</p>

    </subsection>
