    <subsection>
    	<title>Add/Subtract Polynomials</title>

    	<p>Scenario: A company's revenue of selling a certain product can be modeled by <m>y=-0.1x^2+20x-300</m>, where <m>x</m> stands for the number of products sold, and <m>y</m> stands for money in thousand dollars. The cost of producing the product can be modeled by <m>y=5x+100</m>, where <m>x</m> stands for the number of products produced, and <m>y</m> stands for money in thousand dollars. The company's net profit can be calculated by: (net profit)<m>=</m>(revenue)<m>-</m>(cost). Assume all products produced will be sold, use a polynomial to model the company's net profit.</p>

    	<p>We will apply the rule (net profit)<m>=</m>revenue)<m>-</m>(cost), and we have:<md>
	    	<mrow>\amp\phantom{{}=}-0.1x^2+20x-300-(5x+100)</mrow>
	    	<mrow>\amp=-0.1x^2+20x-300-5x-100</mrow>
	    </md>Notice that we distributed <m>-1</m> into the parenthesis:<me>-(5x+100)=-1\cdot(5x+100)=-5x-100</me></p>

    	<p>We can only combine <term>like terms</term>, which are terms with the same variables with the same exponent. In <m>-0.1x^2+20x-300-5x-100</m>, <m>20x</m> and <m>-5x</m> are like terms, and <m>-300</m> and <m>-100</m> are like terms. The full solution is:<md>
	    	<mrow>\amp\phantom{{}=}-0.1x^2+20x-300-(5x+100)</mrow>
	    	<mrow>\amp=-0.1x^2+20x-300-5x-100</mrow>
    		<mrow>\amp=-0.1x^2+15x-400</mrow>
    	</md>Solution: The company's net profit can be modeled by <m>y=-0.1x^2+15x-400</m>, where <m>x</m> stands for the number of products produced, and <m>y</m> stands for money in thousand dollars.</p>

    	<p>Let's look at one more example.</p>

    	<example>
    		<statement>
    			<p>Simplify <m>2x^2+3xy-x^2y-2x(2y-x+y^2)</m>.</p>
    		</statement>
    		<solution>
    			<p><md>
    				<mrow>\amp\phantom{{}=}2x^2+3xy-x^2y-2x(2y+x+y^2)</mrow>
    				<mrow>\amp=2x^2+3xy-x^2y-4xy-2x^2-2xy^2</mrow>
    				<mrow>\amp=-x^2y-2xy^2-xy</mrow>
    			</md></p>
    			<p><m>2x^2</m> and <m>-2x^2</m> canceled out, because their sum is <m>0</m>.</p>
    			<p><m>3xy</m> and <m>-4xy</m> are combined into <m>-xy</m>.</p>
    			<p><m>-x^2y</m> and <m>-2xy^2</m> have no like terms to combine with, so they stay the same.</p>
    			<p>In the final solution, <m>-x^2y</m>, <m>-2xy^2</m> and <m>-xy</m> are not like terms. They have variables with different exponents.</p>
    		</solution>
    	</example>
    </subsection>
